In JavaScript, you can get the size of the screen, current web page, and browser window using the following properties and methods:

window.innerWidth and window.innerHeight: returns the width and height of the viewable area of the browser window
document.documentElement.clientWidth and document.documentElement.clientHeight: returns the width and height of the layout viewport (the part of the page that the user is currently seeing)
window.screen.width and window.screen.height: returns the total width and height of the screen, including the taskbar and other operating system UI elements
window.screenX and window.screenY: returns the x and y coordinate of the top-left corner of the screen relative to the top-left corner of the primary display
window.pageXOffset and window.pageYOffset: returns the distance, in pixels, that the current document has been scrolled horizontally and vertically
Here's an example of how you can use these properties to get the width and height of the screen, the current web page, and the browser window:
// Get window width and height
var windowWidth = window.innerWidth;
var windowHeight = window.innerHeight;

// Get page width and height
var pageWidth = document.documentElement.clientWidth;
var pageHeight = document.documentElement.clientHeight;

// Get screen width and height
var screenWidth = window.screen.width;
var screenHeight = window.screen.height;

// Get screen X and Y position
var screenX = window.screenX;
var screenY = window.screenY;

// Get page X and Y position
