You need to override onSaveInstanceState method to save the state of your activity. In the onSaveInstanceState method, you can put any values you want to save in a Bundle object, which is passed as an argument to the method. Then, in onCreate you can check if savedInstanceState is not null, which means the activity is being restored from a previous state, and get the saved values from the Bundle object.

Here's an updated code example:

java

public class HelloAndroid extends Activity {
  private TextView mTextView = null;
  private static final String TEXT_VIEW_STATE_KEY = "textViewState";

  /** Called when the activity is first created. */
  @Override
  public void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
    super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
    mTextView = new TextView(this);
    if (savedInstanceState == null) {
       mTextView.setText("Welcome to HelloAndroid!");
    } else {
       String textViewState = savedInstanceState.getString(TEXT_VIEW_STATE_KEY);
       mTextView.setText(textViewState);
    }
    setContentView(mTextView);
  }

  @Override
  protected void onSaveInstanceState(Bundle outState) {
    super.onSaveInstanceState(outState);
    outState.putString(TEXT_VIEW_STATE_KEY, mTextView.getText().toString());
  }
}

