This code will work as expected, however there is a potential issue with the performance of the code. When using async/await in a forEach loop, each iteration will run asynchronously, potentially all at the same time, which could lead to a high number of pending asynchronous operations. This can potentially lead to performance issues, such as blocked event loop and increased memory usage.

A better approach could be to use Array.prototype.map() to generate an array of promises, then using Promise.all() to wait for all promises to resolve:

javascript

async function printFiles () {
  const files = await getFilePaths();
  const contents = await Promise.all(files.map(async (file) => {
    return fs.readFile(file, 'utf8');
  }));
  console.log(contents);
}
printFiles();
This way, you can ensure that all file reads are completed in parallel and processed in sequence, avoiding any potential performance issues.

