You can change the class of an HTML element using JavaScript by accessing the element and setting its className property. Here's an example that changes the class of an element with an id of "myElement" when a button is clicked:

javascript

document.getElementById("myButton").addEventListener("click", function() {
  var element = document.getElementById("myElement");
  element.className = "newClass";
});
In this example, document.getElementById("myButton") returns the button element, and addEventListener is used to attach a click event handler to the button. When the button is clicked, the event handler is called, and the class of the element with id "myElement" is changed to "newClass".

You can also use the classList property to change the class of an element. The classList property provides a more convenient and intuitive way to manipulate the classes of an element. Here's an example:

javascript

document.getElementById("myButton").addEventListener("click", function() {
  var element = document.getElementById("myElement");
  element.classList.remove("oldClass");
  element.classList.add("newClass");
});
In this example, element.classList.remove("oldClass") removes the "oldClass" class from the element, and element.classList.add("newClass") adds the "newClass" class to the element.

