A clearfix is a CSS technique used to clear the float property of an element, so that its child elements do not wrap around the floated element but instead appear below it. This is particularly useful when creating multi-column layouts, as it ensures that the columns have equal heights and no overlapping content.

An example of a layout with a clearfix could be a three-column layout, where each column has a float property set to left. Without a clearfix, the parent container may not contain the floated columns, and the footer would appear alongside the floated columns. However, by using a clearfix on the parent container, the parent container will properly contain the floated columns and the footer will appear below them.

Here's an example of a clearfix:

