$scope.$watch and $scope.$apply are two important features in AngularJS that are used to monitor changes in the scope and update the DOM accordingly.

$scope.$watch is used to observe changes in a scope variable and take some action when the value changes. For example, you could use $scope.$watch to update the UI whenever the value of a certain variable changes. Here's an example of how to use $scope.$watch:

php

$scope.$watch('variableName', function (newValue, oldValue) {
  // Take some action when the value changes
});
$scope.$apply is used to apply changes to the scope and trigger a digest cycle. A digest cycle is an AngularJS process that checks all the bound expressions in the scope to see if they have changed and updates the UI if necessary. If you make changes to the scope outside of AngularJS, you need to call $scope.$apply to trigger a digest cycle and update the UI. Here's an example of how to use $scope.$apply:

php

$scope.$apply(function () {
  // Make changes to the scope
});
The connection point between $scope.$watch and $scope.$apply is that $scope.$watch is used to monitor changes in the scope and take action when the value changes, while $scope.$apply is used to apply changes to the scope and trigger a digest cycle to update the UI.

In conclusion, $scope.$watch and $scope.$apply are important features in AngularJS that are used to monitor changes in the scope and update the UI accordingly. Use $scope.$watch to observe changes in a scope variable and take some action when the value changes, and use $scope.$apply to apply changes to the scope and trigger a digest cycle to update the UI.

