Yes, it is possible. You can access the command line arguments passed to an npm script in your JavaScript code by using the process.argv array. The first two elements of the process.argv array are the path to node executable and the path to the script, respectively. The rest of the elements represent the command line arguments passed to the script.

Here's an example of how you could modify your script.js file to access the command line arguments passed via the npm start command:

javascript

const args = process.argv.slice(2);
