A lambda expression in C++11 is a small anonymous function that can be used to pass functionality as an argument to algorithms or as a callable object. They were introduced in C++11 to provide a more concise and readable syntax for writing small, inline functions that can be used as arguments to higher-order functions or as callable objects.

Lambdas capture variables from their surrounding scope and can be used to write functions that operate on those variables, making them useful for writing small, one-off functions that can be passed to algorithms or used as callable objects.

Examples of using lambdas:

Sorting a vector of integers in ascending order:
cpp

vector<int> v = {5, 2, 7, 3};
sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a < b;
});
Filtering a list of strings based on a condition:
vbnet

list<string> lst = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"};
list<string> result;
for_each(lst.begin(), lst.end(), [&result](const string& s) {
    if (s.length() > 5) {
        result.push_back(s);
    }
});
Lambdas were not possible prior to C++11 and their introduction made it easier to write code that was more concise and readable, especially when dealing with functional programming concepts.

